\textbf{Dylan is helping to prepare drinks for a school event. He has 8 litres of orange juice. Each cup can hold \( \frac{3}{4} \) litres of juice.} \\ 
\text{a) How many cups of orange juice can Dylan fill with the 8 litres he has?} \\ 
\text{b) Later, his friend brings another 2 litres and adds it to the juice that is left after filling the cups. What is the total amount of juice left? Write your answer as a mixed number.}

response_dict.solution:
\textbf{a) Number of cups Dylan can fill:} \\
\[
\text{Number of cups} = \frac{8}{\frac{3}{4}}
\]
Dividing 8 by \( \frac{3}{4} \) is the same as multiplying 8 by the reciprocal of \( \frac{3}{4} \):
\[
8 \times \frac{4}{3} = \frac{32}{3}
\]
\(
\frac{32}{3} = 10\frac{2}{3}
\)
So, Dylan can fill 10 full cups and there will be some juice left over.

\textbf{b) Amount of juice left after filling 10 cups:} \\
Juice used for 10 cups:
\[
10 \times \frac{3}{4} = \frac{30}{4} = 7\frac{1}{2} \text{ litres}
\]
Juice left after filling cups:
\[
8 - 7\frac{1}{2} = \frac{16}{2} - \frac{15}{2} = \frac{1}{2} \text{ litre}
\]
Friend brings additional 2 litres:
\[
\frac{1}{2} + 2 = 2\frac{1}{2}\, \text{litres}
\]
\textbf{Final Answer:}
\begin{itemize}
  \item[a)] Dylan can fill \(10\) full cups of orange juice.
  \item[b)] After his friend adds the extra, there are \(2\frac{1}{2}\) litres of juice left.
\end{itemize}

